        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-10-12T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-10-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="57" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d57">
                <head>57. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName>) to President <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d57fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 757,
                        Presidential Correspondence File 1969–1974, Japan, (<persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> Corr) 1969–8 July 1972. Sent for
                        information. Confidential. Stamped notations on the memorandum indicate that
                            <persName corresp="#p_NRM_1">Nixon</persName> saw it on October 23.
                            <persName corresp="#p_HJH_1">Holdridge</persName> sent this memorandum
                        to <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> on October 6,
                        recommending that <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> sign it
                        and send it to the President.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1970-10-12">October 12, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName>’s Reply to Your
                            <rs corresp="recLZdhL4g1ojYmng" type="compound-subject">Letter</rs> on
                        Economic Aid to Cambodia</item>
                </list>
                <p>Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> has replied to your
                        <rs corresp="recLZdhL4g1ojYmng" type="compound-subject">letter</rs> of
                    August 26<note n="2" xml:id="d57fn2">
                        <ref target="#d51">Document 51</ref>.</note> which requested that he give
                    personal attention to the matter of economic aid to Cambodia.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> states that he is watching Cambodian
                    developments with great personal concern. He confirms that the Japanese
                    Government has decided to provide an additional $2 million of emergency
                    assistance in the form of trucks and other commodities and will provide $300
                    thousand for relief of Vietnamese refugees from Cambodia.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> also states that he hopes to
                    contribute to the stabilization and <rs corresp="rectoUaG4WerMOwWn" type="topic">rehabilitation</rs> of the Indochina area by continuing close cooperation
                    with the U.S. He concludes by noting that “he is anxiously looking forward to
                    meeting you” in the course of his presence in the U.S. for the <gloss target="#t_UNGA_1">UNGA</gloss>.</p>
                <p>Our Embassy at Tokyo reported that the Foreign Ministry believed your <rs corresp="recLZdhL4g1ojYmng" type="compound-subject">letter</rs> to <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName> had arrived at just the right time to
                    affect Japanese <pb facs="0192" n="161" xml:id="pg_161"/> consideration of the
                    additional assistance to Cambodia referred to in <persName corresp="#p_SE_1">Sato</persName>’s <rs corresp="recLZdhL4g1ojYmng" type="compound-subject">letter</rs>.</p>
            </div>
